metadata.name: simple things #174
metadata.description:
There‚Äôs beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing ‚Äúd‚Äù followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press ‚Äúd 0‚Äù and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.

metadata.name: In the Edge #277
metadata.description:
./ In the Edge

It's been a long time since your journey began, caring for the ones you love, pursuing your dreams, and giving the best of you. 

Now you know you can't go back, you can't go further, you know your time is coming.

How far did you go? It doesn't matter, you did it right. Your accomplishments will serve well the next generations in their journeys, in their search for themselves.

Now it's time to stop, time to take a moment and contemplate the vast universe.

Soon all of this will be ending.

You did it right.

Embrace the void.
=========
=========


./ Color scheme (feature)
There are 12 color schemes and with each set, specific arrays for color collections for the space, stars, planet, and accent colors. 

These are color schemes in the known universe of "In the Edge":
- Mars visions
- Cyberpunk
- Unknown passenger 
- Renegade
- Primary
- Coral
- r.e.d.
- Machines of an ancient-future 
- The void
- Tinted light 
- Malibu dreams
- Atari (horrendous brown, red and yellowish combinations... I love it)

./ Mountain type (feature)
In the Edge, you will find a mountain, and that mountain will be special, which type will you find?

- Parallela insolitum
- Sandy dunes of the truth
- Wavy uncertainty
- Intrinsic soul ridges
- Cerritulus formationis

./ Mountain direction (feature)
Life is about direction... mountains too.

- Left
- Right
- Left-Right

./ Space scenery
This is the spicy touch, some of the iterations will have animation and others will not, giving you a clear view of the magnificent space in front of you.

- Clean (NOT animated)
- Windy planet (animated)
- Topographic planet (animated)
- Meteor shower (animated)

./ Distance from Earth (feature)
How far did you go? Your travel could be from 1 lightyear to 999,999,999 lightyears (that's a lot of lights and years!). However just a few will pass the barrier of 99,999,999ly.

// Additional perks
./ Planet names 
Planet names are unique and they are conformed by three blocks.

The first block is a conjunction between ancient Latin names and Japanese last names. 

The second block takes the last three characters from the fxhash.

The third block takes three numbers from the number seed obtained from fxrand().

The planet you land will be unique, as unique as you are.

// Controls
./ Pause-Play animation
Because maybe (and just maybe) you want to freeze the perfect moment before closing your eyes.

[Backspace] Pause.
[Enter] Play

Applies to "Space scenery" features windy planet, topographic planet, and meteor shower.

metadata.name: Skyfloors #104
metadata.description:
Skyfloors are a study of perspective, occlusion, color, shape and motion. Occular meditation. A visceral demonstration of noise' ability to emulate natural systems; rolling hills, an angry sea, gentle breezes, crawling skin - all wrapped in 2d isometric projection with a flamboyant twist and a minimal nod to cel animation.

Controls:

right arrow - increase speed in direction 1
left arrow - increase speed in direction 0
P - pause / play
S - save image (increase res in devtools first if you are printing)
L - switch to black outline on brightlines featured pieces
B - switch to solid background on split background featured pieces
D - disable drop shadow

These pieces are pretty feature heavy and include a couple of ultra rare surprises.

All color palettes are procedurally generated, with each edition selecting for 1 of 4 different palette functions. 2 of these functions are open source and developed by meodai:
https://twitter.com/meodai
https://github.com/meodai

https://twitter.com/p4stoboy

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #87
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Sp√∏gelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Ray Drops #92
metadata.description:
Ray Drops plays with the idea of rays that are projected out from a random center point which oscillate at variable frequencies. At each inflection point it has a chance of being intersected by a ring. The inflection points vary in how closely they are spaced and can cluster around the center point or fan all the way out to the edges. 

When run this generative creates a 12 layer SVG vector that is designed to be run on a laser cutter in order to build an in real life woodcut. Each layer is a single contiguous piece with no floating elements so when cut out of wood you end up with 12 layers that can be secured with 10 Chicago screws.  

Learn more and get physical editions: https://alleditions.art/p/ray-drops

Shift P - exports a PNG
Shift S - exports SVG
Shift E - explodes the layers

The 5 rarest mints (once the series is minted out) will receive a free signed physical which can be claimed by an owner of the NFT at anytime. It can be left attached and claimed by any future owner. 

I will also be giving away 5 free signed physicals randomly to people who tweet a picture of their edition and tag @shawnkemp

metadata.name: Luminaries #135
metadata.description:
There is no light without dark.

Luminaries is a study in symmetry, contrast and flow, with a palette inspired by the twelve full moon names. Owning a Luminary enables you to request a signed print for an additional fee. 

You can learn more about features and prints at: https://www.phaust.art/luminary

Each Luminary is composed of moons in various phases. Their layout derived from a handful of geometries. They contrast with their surroundings: filled with glittering stars, inky strokes or solid colour. 

Backgrounds can split along lines of symmetry ‚Äì with dark and light contrasting as strokes seamlessly flow across the two halves. 

Luminaries are alive. They‚Äôre in retrograde once a month, a day in which you‚Äôll see yours in a new light.

------

Collection Size: 158. One for each of the confirmed moons in our solar system.

Palettes: 12 + 1. One for each of the full moons plus a rarer secret palette: Wolf, Snow, Worm, Pink, Flower, Strawberry, Buck, Sturgeon, Harvest, Hunter, Beaver, Cold, ????.

Retrograde: day of the month that your Luminary will change for one day only.

S: to save at high resolution. 

Prints: request from https://www.phaust.art/luminary

metadata.name: ProcGen Entomology #93
metadata.description:
Realtime 3D in-browser procedural generation of insect-like models, with a look reminiscent of vintage entomology illustrations.

The project is about the fact that insects are cool first and foremost.
This is also about nostalgia.

Everything is procedural except for the font. The exposed features only describe the most visible parts.

I wrote mord words, about where it came from, and some technical details on the procedural aspect at:
https://ulucode.com/projects/entomology/

GPU Required!

Interface : 
Space : show/hide menu
Mouse Left : Rotate
Mouse Right : Pan
Mouse Middle/Wheel : Zoom

Captures only work in Live mode.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #768
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.
